  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">PEPFAR Zambia seeks to build on the positive gains realized by the Government of Zambia&#x2019;s (GRZ) investment in social cash transfers with regard to health, nutrition and household economic resiliency. The intent is to support GRZ to be more innovative with their social protection initiatives at both the policy and operational levels. On a policy level, the goal is to influence the current eligibility criteria to include HIV/AIDS sensitivity along with the existing high household dependency ratios. Operationally, the goal is to standardize approaches to providing care to households receiving cash. Also to introduce an asset-building component that provides the next step up from cash only. Activities would complement and fill gaps in the existing social cash transfer program and would be undertaken in close collaboration with other social protection stakeholders. Use of the PIO mechanism allows for the direct funding of UNICEF which is the primary stakeholder supporting GRZ&#x2019;s social cash transfer program. Global evidence suggests that cash alone is not the powerful change agent needed to achieve resilient households and support HIV disease management and prevention. &#x201C;Cash plus care&#x201D; provides greater impact on health behaviours, especially relevant to HIV and AIDS. USAID will leverage care services through the OVC platform with an emphasis on HIV case finding, adherence support and accessing community care and treatment services. Activities will support the rollout and expansion of GRZ&#x2019;s social protection program through PEPFAR funded service-delivery programs, frontline and manager workforce development, and country-specific evidence building on how appropriate social protection policies and instruments might yield improved 90-90-90 outcomes or perform more efficiently.</narrative>
  </description>
